## Summary

Debugged 33 malformed session summary files ("Prompt is too long" errors from Apr 15), traced root cause to transcript truncation + guard false positives + haiku context limits. Brainstormed refactor: decouple capture from summarization via manifest pattern (vault-as-index, lazy synthesis). Drafted requirements doc, underwent 5-persona review, expanded to comprehensive 7-unit plan addressing concurrency, idempotency, and oversized-transcript handling. Tightened plan against document review findings (P0: locking primitive, non-destructive --force, explicit scope justification). Completed Unit 1 (5 foundation libs: vault, frontmatter, git, lockfile, manifest) with full test-first coverage. Units 2–7 remain.

## Extraction Candidates

- **Manifest pattern for session capture** (concept) — Decoupling capture (deterministic, fast, always succeeds) from summarization (LLM-expensive, retryable, derived cache) using immutable manifest + lazy synthesis. Solves silent data loss, enables re-summarization, supports cross-session queries. Exemplar of "vault-as-index" architecture vs. vault-as-content-store.
- **Hierarchical chunk reduction for LLM summarization** (concept) — Strategy for handling transcripts that exceed LLM context: group turns into chunks ≤ threshold, reduce partial summaries hierarchically, truncate single turns in-place with markers. Eliminates hard "Prompt is too long" failures without loss of session scope.
- **Session capture architecture (2026-04-19 refactor plan)** (source-summary) — 7-unit plan decoupling session capture from summarization; includes manifest schema, CLI commands, migration strategy, concurrency safety, and skill contract updates. Load-bearing decisions: single-machine transcripts, lazy-on-read summarization, test-first for Unit 1.
